multilateral agreements, Japan proposed East Asia's first multilateral security forum in the early 1990s, emerging as a regional leader. Overcoming Isolationism explores what led to this surprising about-face and offers a corrective to the misperception that Japan's security strategy is reactive to US pressure and unresponsive to its neighbors. Paul Midford draws on newly released official documents and extensive interviews to reveal a quarter century of Japanese leadership in promoting regional security cooperation. He demonstrates that Japan has a much more nuanced relationship with its neighbors and has played a more significant leadership role in shaping East Asian security than has previously been recognized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aSecurity, InternationalzEast Asia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Arms Control.2bisacsh  aASEAN Regional Forum (ARF).  aASEAN.  aAlliance Security Dilemma.  aCommon Security.  aCooperative Security.  aFear of Abandonment.  aFear of Entrapment.  aJapan.  aRegional Security Multilateralism.  areassurance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069218140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503613096423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503613096.jpg  a978-3-11-069218-1  SUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978